This is the Basic Raptor, a free demonstration build of mine in 28mm/1-56th scale that I have shrunk to a quarter of its regular size for games of New Epic, AT-18, and other similar games.

These are tiny pieces. Some weapon barrels are as thin as support structures. Turn back. Down this road, madness awaits.

Take great care in post-processing. Print multiples, in case you snap something. Use heat to loosen supports before you try and free the objects. Use a soft toothbrush and light strokes when cleaning.

Otherwise, these take about 14 or 15 grams of material. You can make a few mistakes, since a kilogram bottle of resin contains potentially 66 or more Tiny Terrors.

Join my Discord to show off your little guys.
 https://discord.gg/7PyEqpkARb

Of join my Patreon at www.patreon.com/johnbearross to get discounts on my paid files, and support my caffeine habit.

Enjoy!

Best,
John Bear Ross

The Ruzisa Pattern Void Yacht is a luxurious, heavily customized reinterpretation of the Imperial Light Cruiser â€“ Geonus II Pattern, repurposed not for war, but for status, prestige, and interstellar presence. Designed for use by planetary governors, noble dynasties, and high-ranking Rogue Traders, these ships are symbols of wealth, power, and refined taste within the Imperium.

While it retains elements of the original cruiserâ€™s silhouette, the Ruzisa Pattern strips away most of its military infrastructure in favor of ornate architecture, custom superstructures, and ceremonial void chapels. The hull is reworked with lavish interiors, towering galleries, personal spires, arboretums, and frescoed observation domesâ€”each vessel becoming a unique, spacefaring masterpiece.

Defensive capabilities remain: void shields and automated turrets provide a respectable level of protection, though the Ruzisa is not designed to endure the rigors of frontline conflict. Its most defining feature, however, is its colossal sub-light propulsion ring, a rare and fragile system that encircles its primary engine. This allows the yacht to achieve extraordinary cruising speeds, gliding through voidspace with unmatched smoothness. The cost and delicacy of this propulsion method prevent its use in most military contexts, but for a civilian vessel built to stay clear of danger and move with grace, it is ideal.

Each Ruzisa is custom-built, and no two are alike. Their baroque hulls may carry heraldry, relic vaults, or entire entourages of retainers, artists, or private militias. They are palaces with engines, and they serve their masters not only as shipsâ€”but as thrones among the stars.

The battlefields of the grim-dark future are scattered will the everyday materiel of the industrial and military complex required to process war on a galactic scale.

This set offers a sample of a cargo crate, cargo hauler, blank trailer, and pallet of materiel.

These could be printed at 200% for 15mm gaming terrain, or, if you are ambitious, 400% for 28-32mm scale gaming. The models are sufficiently detailed to be printed at larger scale, yet simple and robust enough to print at their intended 6-8mm scale.

This set contains 4 STLs; a sample of the full set, available here:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/epic-cargo-road-train-scatter-terrain-6mm-8mm-scale

The full set allows you to customise your selection. It can be used to create cargo 'road trains', linking multiple trailers and cargo containers to create thematic barriers for your miniatures to take cover behind, or individual pieces to add character to the bases of larger miniatures.

They would also make suitable 'toys' what could be added to 28-32mm scale models, adding a layer of horror and inhumanity to the devastation surrounding your grim-dark characters.

The crane and defence trailer is compatible with my other Epic tank turrets, so can be replaced with any of the turrets in this collection:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/8mm-scale-grim-dark-tank-turrets-of-russ-nedius

Please see my other designs for other wargaming STLS.

I am an amateur enthusiast 3D designer, and appreciate all support and constructive feedback. Please check out my other designs for more wargame models, and please consider following me, post a make, and enjoy my models. If you would like to support my work, please leave a comment, like the design, or make a donation via my profile! Thanks!

The Tech Shanty Tower One is designed for 6mm / 8mm games in mind. This kit includes two versions of the same structure (one with commercial signs that are flat, the other one with three dimensional signs). Also included are two signs that can be added on top of the building. The war for Rennerâ€™s World is not going well for the embattled forces defending their home from the invading Kaiju. The abominable walking mega-fauna are now manifesting new abilities and incorporating cybernetic systems and replacement limbs, hinting at a more sinister force behind the invasion through the world-gates.

To compensate for this growing threat, the members of the Renner Defense League command staff have dusted off old plans from the Project Gigante design competition, the JagdHund, or Hunting Hound. JagdHund was a concept once deemed too large and unwieldy for the battlefield, but it has been recalled to the forefront as the threat literally grows larger.

JagdHundâ€™s paired heavy gatling weapons are capable of dealing with hordes or point targets with equal ease, while the dorsal-mounted main gun, a superheavy maser cannon, is dedicated to frying and boiling the larger monsters emerging through the dimensional breaches. The directed energy weapon is an experiment, and has not been properly developed to withstand the rigors of close-range combat with kaiju. Plans are in the works to add different weapons and countermeasures to the JagdHund arsenal.

The majority of the Hund crews are composed of Quads, or quadruple amputees, wounded veterans and civilian volunteers who have been maimed and disfigured by the invading megafauna. Body modifications are sometimes necessary for final adjustments, but replacement limbs are provided. Quads came about originally from the Assault Raptor program, but have proved to be an invaluable asset in the fight against the invading monsters.

Kushal Heavy Industries, based 214 jumps deep in the Fourth Gate Network of worlds, is a renowned manufacturer of arms, both for their economy of material usage and rock bottom pricing structures.

They recently have taken their surrounding upstream and downstream neighborhood of dimensions by storm with the release of the Basic Raptor, a clean-sheet refinement of the datacore salvaged long ago from an unknown, nuked-out world.

That datacore gave the Realms Project Raptor, a broad category of light mechs that serve as scouts and fast attack platforms, taking the fight to the enemy with speed and devastating firepower.

Kushal's version is a stark, bare-bones battle platform that is intended for the customer who needs to put warheads on foreheads, without any need for frivolity, pomp, or circumstance. Or cockpit padding, as many a bruised pilot can testify.

The Basic Raptor is sneered at by some, but admired by others for its uncompromising simplicity, ruggedness, and singularity of purpose.

Many smaller defense contractors and boutique armor shops are taking stock Basic Raptors and modifying them with fancier weapons and armor packages. Assassins from the Kushal Heavy Industries Legal Department have been dispatched through the world-gates to deliver enhanced cease-and-desist notifications, to some lethal effect.

------------------------

I give a rolling monthly 50% discount code for my entire inventory, including new releases as I put them out.

I also have a Discord, The Madness of John Bear Ross. We're a collection of mecha-heads, painters, builders, and other artists who love giant walking nightmares. Here's the invite link...
https://discord.gg/7PyEqpkARb

Enjoy!

Other mechs are shown for size ref purposes, and are available separately.

This is a set for creating a city building as a terrain for any wargame in 1/285 (6mm) scale. The set allows you to assemble both an intact (undamaged) buildings and a destroyed ones (ruins). You can assemble a building of any height you want by printing the required number of intermediate floors.


There is one option with square windows (marked with number 1) and the second with rounded windows (marked with number 2).


To make it easier to paint the windows, I made it a separate piece that can be painted in advance (for example, with spray paint) and inserted inside the walls.


I also made a set of interior parts in case you don't use windows or want to make glass from transparent material.

Description :

1

I personally love Warhound Titans and have a full size one printed and painted, though I was never a fan of how the Vulcan Mega Bolters look like a brick with a magazine which would run empty after 5 seconds of continuous fire. This is my attempt to make something more visually striking and with a magazine more suitable for such an immense weapon. The arm mount is sized to other arm mounts which can be found on Cults for free. Just to mix things up a bit, I created a version of the Mega Bolter with twin short barrels and long barrels. The full pack comes with two complete Bolters with short/long barrel along with separate parts for those who want to print separate objects. As always, hope you all enjoy and don't hesitate to contact me with any concerns you may have.

The photographed Bolter is a test print using Nylon 12.

**Iota-HU, Pickup Truck**

This file is another remix/remaster of a file made by [TheDude21](https://www.thingiverse.com/thedude21/designs) (check him out and give him a tip, if you like). Much like the previous Glade-S, I very much liked the core Cyberpunk stylings of this vehicle concept and thought that it would make a nice adaption into a 'lower' tech level universe setting as a civilian hovercraft vehicle at the 6mm scale setting.

**About the Design.** Despite the superficial resemblance's to the original design, this project actually took quite a lot of time to remaster, because I wanted to remove as many of the 'hard-angle' edges as possible. This should make the model much better to orientate for supports and 3D print on a resin system. (zoom right in on the file to compare it with the original, if you like!)

**Other Designs.** This model set is intended to be compatible with the other 6mm (true-scale) and Hex(33) (hex scale) SciFi terrain sets that I have released on [Cults 3D](https://cults3d.com/en/users/Shiaic3D/creations) and other locations, [GumRoad](https://shiaic3d.gumroad.com/), [Printables](https://www.printables.com/@Shiaic3D/models) and [Thingiverse](https://www.thingiverse.com/shiaic1/designs).

Please search my other designs for more models of a similar type and theme.

****************
**Creativity Powered by Patreon.** This model is a remix of free files and parts available elsewhere. However, the time and effort to remix them into a model set like this were enabled with the support of my generous [Patreon](https://www.patreon.com/Shiaic3D) backers, who gain exclusive access to remixes like this for a temporary period well before it is released wider.

Please check out my [Patreon](https://www.patreon.com/Shiaic3D) if you want to support the creation of more remix projects like this, or gain access to my other remastered works and/or unique terrain creations for 6mm tabletop wargaming.

**Leave a Tip.** Alternatively, please feel free to leave a tip if you like this model and think it is merited (and don't forget to tip any original designers) - an occasional coffee helps fuel the creative effort and sustains morale :)

**Other Files.** Additionally, if you want to find more of my unique 6mm wargame terrain and building creations and other 3D designs, check out my [GumRoad](https://shiaic3d.gumroad.com/) shop or please also see my other unique designs on [Cults 3D](https://cults3d.com/en/users/Shiaic3D/creations). **Glade-S, civilian HC**

This file is a remix & remaster of a file originally made by [Pietia](https://www.thingiverse.com/Pietia). I had looked at this 28mm scale model Cyberpunk Sci-Fi car and thought that it would be a cool design to adapt and remix as a civilian-model Sci-Fi hover car for use at 6mm scale.

**About the Design.** I have taken the original 3D model by Pieta and remastered it slightly, adapting it more for the 6mm scale size where some of the detail at 28mm scale was either redundant or required some further adjusting to account for detail creep or dissolution (if printed). I then created the Hovercraft 'skirt' separately and melded these two main feature components together. Finally, I created some other new detail features as well as further adjusting some of the existing features to bring it all together more holistically as an integrated overall design that works on its own.

And voila! hopefully, it does.

**Other Designs.** This model set is intended to be compatible with the other 6mm (true-scale) and Hex(33) (hex scale) SciFi terrain sets that I have released on [Cults 3D](https://cults3d.com/en/users/Shiaic3D/creations) and other locations, [GumRoad](https://shiaic3d.gumroad.com/), [Printables](https://www.printables.com/@Shiaic3D/models) and [Thingiverse](https://www.thingiverse.com/shiaic1/designs).

A complete collection of retro-themed Gothic Ruins for table top gaming. These are the full set of 20 ruins that make up the full set of the sample set released earlier, available here: https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/retro-gothic-corner-ruins-set-1

Included in this set are 20 corner ruins, the floor piece for the raised platform on the two tallest corner ruins, plus two floor templates in case anyone wants to break them up a bit for some floor details on the ground level.

Inspired by the cardboard terrain I used in my youth, these turn those 2D flat terrain pieces into fully 3D models, to look more fitting on a modern gaming table!

Scaled to suit 28mm-32mm models, I actually designed them to be printed out at 50% scale for 15mm gaming. They even work well all the way down to 25% scale for 8mm gaming!

Perfect for reliving past wargaming experiences, or for giving your current games a bit of a Retro theme!

Please check out my other wargaming models including the first part of this set, and if you like this set, please consider liking the file, following me, or even making a donation! I love seeing what people do with my models, so please post a make once you've printed them out. I am an amateur, hobby-level designer, and any support helps keep me motivated and supports the hobby activities I can do! Thanks!

Let's face it: Even in the far future, people are still obsessed with efficiency, doing more with less. So it is with maintaining the Imperious Leader's far-flung dominion, and the most efficient method of moving stuff is still the train. And when you have enemies, those trains make sweet, juicy targets, necessitating adding arms and armor to repel the bad guys.

This set includes not only nine different train cars, but compatible track segments. The various train cars have round guide lugs on the underside that serve to keep the cars centered on the tracks.

The GothiTech Armored Train includes:

- Armed Locomotive
- Flatbed Car
- Boxcar
- Tanker Car
- Passenger Car
- Nuclear Fuel Car
- Artillery Car (cannon prints separately and can be mounted up for firing or down for travel)
- Troop Car (includes mounting points for two turrets)
- Air Defense Car (includes two antiaircraft missile turrets)
- Five Track Segments (Straight Single, Curved Single, Y-Split, Straight Double, and Curved Double)

This locally-produced heavy fighter, distantly related to the more commonly encountered Thunderbolt, featured heavily in the closing days of the imperial civil war. With poor maneuverability at low altitudes and a dangerously exposed propulsion system, the craft was poorly suited for ground attack work. However, its speed and performance at high altitudes, combined with a pair of lethally accurate long-barreled autocannons made the fighter especially dangerous when either escorting or intercepting bombers and reconnaissance aircraft. Fighting on both sides during the conflict, it was ultimately a shortage of pilots with combat experience that led to horrific casualty rates among its pilots.

Compatible with any 8mm scale wargame. Fits most standard flight stands. Comes in air and ground versions with a variety of ordnance.

Using the fantastic model made by FELIXTHECRAZY (along another Ridgerunner proxy that dissapeared time ago and i dont know who made it), i designed this vehicle mostly for my Squat miners, but i think is suitable for Genestealers Cults too.

I cant assure if is a proper Ridgerunner proxy, because i think this model is smaller, but i added all the weapons and accesories listed in GSC army book for the vehicle in case that someone want to use it in that way. Maybe re-escaling it a bit is enough, but i dont how much, i have never seen a real Ridgerunner model before.

The original model is a single piece, meant to be printed in resin, but my experience printing vehicles in resin is not the best, so i prefer print them on PLA. With that in mind, i separated some pieces of the model to make it suitable for FDM printers, specially small parts that will probably break when you try to remove supports, then the best is print them apart and glue them after. Refer the pics to look where each piece goes

Weapons and accesories are small and detailed, and were designed to be printed in resin. You can try to print them in FDM of course, but they will lost a lot of detail, specially with the mining laser.

About the Spotter, i choose a more "technological" option instead a guy with binoculars. It makes more sense i think, and it saved me a lot of work :P

I included the center hull as one piece and in halves. I printed it as one piece, but I think it's easier and faster to print two pieces. Your choice.

I dont discard make some aditional weapons and accesories in the future.

The M.A.D.C.A.T. (Medical Assistance and Diagnosis Cyber-Altered Task) is the latest innovation in Squat medical technology. A robotic unit (not heresy), all-terrain, portable (if you have a Rhino, Chimera or a large backpack) and capable of taking an ER wherever it is needed. Equipped with a whole collection of sharp, pointy and no doubt painful things, the M.A.D.C.A.T. It is designed to assist Squats medical teams in their daily tasks, providing comprehensive diagnosis and hands-on support to treat virtually any field situation, no matter how serious.

As long as it's not reattaching heads and necks, regenerating vaporized limbs, or picking up pieces of you scattered everywhere.

Update 06/14/23: As you can see in the pictures, this thing is printable. My FDM couldn't print the bellows for some reason, so I made an alternative "hull" model with these parts simpilfied. I don't think this is a problem for resin printers.

Just dont forget that removing supports is part of the fun and you need to break some..."eggs" to make an omelette. A very tiny plastic omelett with even tinier plastic eggs.

Here's my set of modular building elements that allows you to build gothic-like structures for your wargaming terrain. I designed it for FDM printers.

The initial idea was to be able to create simple gothic-like walls in both undamaged and damaged form, so this is the reason why there are no floor tiles just yet.

There are no fancy connecting mechanism - use the glue, Luke! I prefer to use quick-drying basing glue.

**1.0v - Initial Release**

- Includes 27 wall and column modules.

**Updates**

- 18-07-2023: after some more printing, I can confirm that resizing the modules down to 80% still works great. I can also confirm that the modules print easily on a resin printer - with no supports, placed directly on the build plate. To save resin, you can hollow the columns (don't forget to add the drainage holes).

Here are twelve, perhaps crude, though definitely brutal close combat hand-to-hand melee assault weapons. They are intended to allow give you some extra options and conversion bits for your Chaos Cultists. You do love Chaos Cultists don't you?? Though I think they are generic enough to work for most human sized miniatures in any grim and dark dystopian future setting from undercity gangs, to wasteland scavengers, rebels, organized criminal thugs, and pretty much any kind of poorly equipped ne'er-do-wells up to no good.

Here are the 12 unique weapons:

-- Axe
-- Club
-- Hammer1
-- Hammer2
-- Knife1
-- Knife2
-- Mace
-- Pick
-- Pipe
-- Scimitar
-- Sword1
-- Sword2

Each weapon comes in three STL variants:
1) weapon by itself
2) weapon held in a right hand
3) weapon held in a right hand (hand has a nub to socket into wrists)

Knife1 and Knife2 have four variants each, two with the blade held normally and two with the blade held ready to stab. You can mirror the weapons with hands on them to create left-handed versions. All total that comes to 68 different options. You can use these files for physical or digital conversions as you see fit. They are also Creative Common Licensed so that you can modify them as you please and then share your own innovations.

Enjoy, and may the Dark Gods favor you.

https://cults3d.com/en/users/Red-warden-miniatures/creations

*********************
Commentary :

All of the design backgrounds were based on the Roguetrader (1st Edition) and the 2nd and 3rd Edition designs.

As always, based on the design of the time, I mixed the design sensibilities of the present era.

Personally, I recommend that the size of the shoulder pad is 105-108%, and the size of the head is 95%. (That looks good.)

I got a lot of help from my colleague, LegioXIVguy, in determining the ratio and size. So the overall size is about between New edition Chaos space marines and Primaris marines.

Please enjoy the Retro work.

My take on the standard imperial cruisers for battlefleet gothic.

This design is intentionally very close to the original sculpts, though some creative liberties were taken.

All parts have holes for 1x2 mm round magnets so they can be easily magnetized.

WARNING: This project is still heavily WIP. The tolerances on some of the modular parts are a bit off and they may require some force to assemble. It is currently recommended to just glue the head and ram in place, and only magnetize the weapons. If the scale seems wrong on a part, try scaling it up or down by a factor of 10.

ImperialCruiserComplete.stl represents a Lunar-class cruiser.

Improved versions of all parts, more complete cruisers, a main body variant for battlecruisers and nova cannons are all hopefully coming soon.

The Underhive Poverty Outreach Team are made up of the members of the Noble Houses. They are equipped with special suits of armor, which they use to stock the many food banks found in the Underhive.

Horace's role in the team, as the bionic tray-holder guy, is to descend the many flights of stairs from Tesco (Spire branch) to the underhive with an entire pallet of donated tinned pineapple chunks in each hand. His powerfists come with a secondary weapon of two rows of firework-launchers which he keeps loaded in hope of a Labour Party victory - when it finally comes after 38,000 years.

This is my entry for the next [28mag challenge](https://28-mag.com/2021/01/12/the-28magchallenge-for-2021/).

Beltanya Zukhal is a legal clerc of the Administratum whose task is to record anything and everything, from dead fluotubes to Astra Militarum empty Autocannon cases and daily casualty on the battlefield. She even records the number of downloads of her STL template.
As part of her missions, she frequently goes on field trips to accompany Regimental HQ staff (where she carries a sidearm for self defence).

It is on one of such missions that she met with Inquisitor Johevian of the Ordo Aegis. Now she works for him undercover and has even been sighted with him as part of his retinue.

As always, "Watch" if you want to be informed of any updates.

Loads of containers and container handling goodness! Stationary container cranes, walking container cranes, quad container haulers, container skates, container land trains, and more! A variety of container stacks! A confusing plethora of files! These containers and handling equipment make a great container yard terrain setup, or just lots of small vehicles and scatter terrain to give your battlefields some life.

Models include:
The big stationary container crane is presented in several models, with the container 'rack' in different positions. A seperate part is included for a container hanging from cables.

Quad mech 'walking' container cranes in several models. They can also use the hanging container part if you print the version with no rack. (Its another quad industrial mech!)

The container Train is a multi-part model of a tractor and one or more trailers to make up a 'train' that is meant to service the stationary cranes. Empty trailers are included along with those loaded with one or two containers.

Container Stackers are trucks with piston lifts that allow them to drive over single containers, or lift high enough to double-stack. Handy for moving containers but can't stack as high as the big walking cranes.

Container skates are a variation of the mech skates (see the mech repair posting!) either loaded or unloaded; they're an alternative to the trains for moving containers and look best when being loaded/unloaded by the walking cranes.

Container stacks in different configurations and heights, along with a few single containers.

A Buildermech with a container flatbed is also included (See my Buildermech posting for lots of other options - the crane version would also be handy in a container yard. Also, see my modular ships to have something the big cranes can offload!

Modeled in 6mm scale.

Some time ago I was felt very inspired by the 40K scale imperator titan from Zammerak you can find here in Cults, so I started remixing my own head variant, more close to the titan in the Titandeath cover, a design closer to the original Epic imperator model and featuring a full detailed interior cockpit. I used for the remix the head from the zammerakÂ´s titan and a low poly faceplate model here in cults, apart from hundreds of bits from Cults and Thingiverse for the interior detailing.
The size is calibrated to lore 40K scale titan, of about 95-110 cms. ItÂ´s compatible with my Imperator model and GrantÂ´s model but it will need to be rescalated about -25%
In the plans if fits OK but when IÂ´ve printed it needed a lot of sanding in the cap part :-( Version 2 features a simplified cap with better fit.
The interior features complete cockpit with monitors, controls, a holographic display and a hiden room bellow with as little chapel and 2 servitors. Hope you like it :-) Complete crew (2 moderatii and 1 princeps) in the donators rewars folder.

This model is remixed from this models:

- For the base I used zammerakÂ´s titan head, you can fin the complete titan in Cults free Here: https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/titanic-church-delivery-system
- For the faceplate I choose this model from Fantabuloustexan, Here free in Cults3D: https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/various/walkin-church-titan-head
- And hundreds of bits from Thingiverse and Cults3D

The perfect restaurant for watching S7 broadcasts or kicking back with the local mercs for a beer. This building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support placing units on top in all hexes for playability. The top of version B has additional supports for two edge hexes for extra stability. It is 1 level tall in most areas, except for the front two hexes where it is 1.5 levels tall, if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are eight files. For each of version A and B, one has the building on hexes, another is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions that have the text removed from the front of the building. Using the NoText versions, you can paint custom names on the front, print off logos to attach, or leave it blank.

As always, tipping is appreciated at: paypal.me/rainingfire416

Notable features:
-An in-universe themed restaurant name.
-Fantastic custom logo and details to give it a proper BBQ joint look.
-Detailed design including doors, windows, and a detailed roof with greebles.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

This is a shoulder/carapace mounted Turbolaser Destructor (twin turbolaser) for use with Stroganoff's Battleduke Warstrider model.

It's a mashup of this Apocalypse Rocket Launcher by totenpf:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4814519
...the turbolaser barrels from this Wardog:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/lucius-wardog-titan
...and part of the Laser Blaster model that comes with the Battleduke
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/epic-scale-mars-warlord-titan

I took all the bits, chopped them around, scaled them to fit and mashed them together.

It should fit exactly onto the Battleduke model if you print them both at the same scale. If you want to use it with an AT-scale model you'll need to scale it up a bit; probably about 125% but I don't know exactly as I haven't tried it and I don't currently have any AT models to measure.

The model is slightly asymmetrical. I think it works better on the right shoulder; mirror it for the left.

This is an enormous heavy energy weapon arm for huge battle robots. The elbow joint has a well for a 5mm magnet in it, along with interface ports to make it compatible with the WB series of slightly-bigger-than-huge battle robots.

Edit 4/21/22: The original Heavy Turbo Cannon was kind of a chonky lad. I made an upgraded 'Slim' version, essentially scaling it down by 15%, then extending the barrel and rejiggering the mounts to fit it again - giving it a lighter, sleeker form factor, while still remaining a giant fuckoff cannon. I also smoothed out some of the geometry to give the main chassis a more rounded look.

I also went and smoothed out the geometry on the original one while I was at it - both are included in this download, the original being the 'Big Smoothed' version, while the newer lighter model is the 'Slim' version. Enjoy!

Fixed a geometry error with the trim on the model, uploaded as the 'Fix' versions. Sorry for the inconvenience.

Designed up this dealer button to use in home games or have just as something laying around for any poker fan. It was inspired by a dealer button in Pokerstars VR.

Printing:

Ring - Infil to add weight, supports needed for spade inset. Letter embossing doesn't need it.
Spade - Infil to add weight, no supports
Letters - Print flat, already scaled to fit nicely in the embossing
Star - Infil to add weight.

Full print with 4x4x4 walls/top/bottom and 38% infil came to about 48g in weight.

Glue in lettering and spade. Star may need minor sanding but should push fit into the space tightly and not need anything else to secure it.

It's a big quad industrial mech! The Drillermech is a BIG mech (for 6mm anyway), intended to operate as an all terrain mobile drilling platform, able to sink a well just about anywhere you might need it to go. 

The model is a little bit elaborate. The default parts are divided to make printing less of a headache. The original .3mf file is included in case you feel the need to split it up further. (Microsoft 3D builder is a decent part splitter and is free).

This mech is modeled from real drilling platforms, with pipe handling arms, a rather large top drive, iron roughneck, and so forth. The big cylinder in the back is the pipe rack, intended to be reloaded from the back or just swapped for another full cylinder. Just remember - don't shoot the active drilling rig, you have no idea what it's sitting on!

Also included is a 'waterline' model for those rigs deployed in shallow water areas.

This is a simple remix of the Savannah Mister scout hovercraft https://www.sarna.net/wiki/Savannah_Master.

I took the design by LeoCeballos, but wanted it to be more proportional in scale to the old official Savannah Master miniatures produced by Ral Partha (to match my collection).

A classy Chinese restaurant to add to your city, this building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support placing units on top in all hexes for playability. It is 1 level tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are four files. One has the building on hexes, another is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions that have the text removed from the front of the building. Using the NoText versions, you can paint custom names on the front, print off logos to attach, or leave it blank.

As always, tipping is appreciated at: paypal.me/rainingfire416

**Notable features:**
-Detailed design including doors, windows, and a detailed roof with greebles.
-Asian-inspired font used for the store name.
-Large yin-yang logo made and placed on the front of the restaurant.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

This is my design remix to properly make the most of those soda or beer can you drink while painting or playing warhammer40k. Give them a new life and make they look really cool in your game table.

This pack includes only the pieces to build the preview:

- 2 bottom supports and rings
- front imperial hatch
- back ventilation grille
- side control panel
- side pipe to the ground
- top ventilation fan
- top human access hatch and the ladder to get there

v2 (2021-04-11):

- Added parts needed to build a vertical container with a 330ml slim can. Only needs 2 beds to print in less than 4 hours.

v2.2 (2021-06-20):

- Added Adeptus Mechanicus symbol to 330ml slim version (also can be used as top part in the regular version). Thanks to @Turtlebot for the suggestion.

Also includes the pre-assembled project files for popular slider softwares. 3 beds for short-printing times and get a tank ready in a single day.

- Tijnemanske (for his amazing "soda can terrain" design. Search him in thingiverse)
- SevenUnited (for the control panel)

- me (I've made the ladder from scratch ^_^)

IT'S THE LATE 80's, IN SPAAAAACE!

Everyone has mohawks and piercings!
Industrial Metal head anarchists galore!

Here are a few heavy weapons options for your human sized dudes and dudettes, Inspired by classic Necromunda. I give you low tech solutions to deadly problems.

The BRRT Supression Stubber:
All style and zero substance with this over designed chunk of metal, it'll throw roughly bullet shaped things in a roughly straight line. You'll need steroids top deal with kick up though.

Australian Stubber:
The bullets go in ..... UPSIDE DOWN!?
That's right, make gravity your accomplice when you mow down a MF with this retro gravity fed SOB.

Firehazard:
Loaded with homemade fuel that you can dink in a pinch to get your liver upset, the fire hazard is dangerous to everyone, that's cool right? OSHA are nerds!

BAGL (The Ga-chunk):
The Bow Assisted Grenade Launcher or the BAGL (sometimes called the Ga-chunk!) on account of the sound it makes.
Who says you need fancy gas assisted launching mechanisms? Who had the bright idea to try and launch explosives with smaller explosions?
That guy is dead, because those Ideas are hard to execute.

Why go complicated when you can just update a medieval stonebow with modern polymers and alloys.

Possibly the only "stealth" grenade launcher on the market!

Resin would be Ideal, but I've printed the smaller assault rifles I made on FDM and they barely look any more trash than other necromunda weapons! (0.2 nozzle is necessary)

In the 31st century, this originally Canadian business has rebranded to be even more popular! This building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support placing units on top for playability. It is 2 levels tall on the higher levels and 1 level tall on the lower levels if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

This is a two part print. Part 1 of the building can be used standalone as any large commercial building if you print the version without text and a logo. Part 2 is an automotive center add-on that can be placed on either side of the main building to make it larger, as seen in the photos above.

There are six files. Two have the building sections on hexes, two are hexless so that you can print the ones that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions of Part 1 that have the text removed from the front of the building. Using the NoText versions, you can populate your tabletop with custom commercial/big-box stores by painting names on the front or printing off logos to attach.

As always, tipping is appreciated at: paypal.me/rainingfire416

Notable features:
-Based off of a very popular Canadian business, using a similar font and building design style.
-Detailed design including large front windows, two main entrances, garage doors, windows, and bollards to protect the building from bad drivers.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

Always waiting to spring up on their enemy, this restaurant chain seems to spread all across the sphere. This building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support a unit placed on top for the hex locations. It is 1 level tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are four files. One has the building on hexes, another is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions that have the text removed from the front of the building. The versions with text may only look good when printed in resin, so if you print with FDM you may prefer to print the NoText files. In that case, you can paint a name on the front, print off a logo to attach, or leave it blank.

Notable features:
-Building design is based on a version of the real-world equivalent restaurant. The angled entrances in particular.
-Detailed design including doors, windows, a drive through, and a detailed roof with greebles.
-The NoText versions work perfectly well as any generic commercial building. Feel free to be creative and print off logos to decorate your city!

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

A cute little Japanese restaurant for anywhere in the universe, this building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support a unit placed on top for all 4 hex locations. It is 1 level tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are four files. One has the building on hexes, another is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions that have the text removed from the front of the building. The versions with text may only look good when printed in resin, so if you print with FDM you may prefer to print the NoText files. In that case, you can paint a name on the front, print off a logo to attach, or leave it blank.

Notable features:
-Nice little window and door designs that evoke a Japanese feel.
-Detailed design including doors, windows, a ladder to the roof, and a detailed roof with greebles.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

-The large F statue is 2 levels tall but will not support a unit. It is meant as a decoration. It will require a little support to print nicely.
-The billboard is also 2 levels tall and may support a unit if you are careful, but it is also meant as a decoration. It will require a little support to print nicely.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

In the distant future, humanity has learnt that hexagonal buildings are superior!

They're hexagonal residential buildings, for 6mm / 1:285 gaming - primarily Battletech but also Epic 40k and other games at that scale.

The buildings are combinations of hexagonal towers that equate to level 1, 2 and 3 within Battletech. I've set level 1 at about 25mm which allows small mechs to still see over them and level 2 at about 55mm which blocks visibility of even the largest mechs I've tested. Each level after that goes up 30mm.

They're designed to fit within the "standard" Battletech map hexes of 33mm flat edge to flat edge as is used in the current boxed sets. They also have a roof designed to allow Mech models to be placed on them.

The models are designed to be mostly supportless on an FDM printer and have printed fine on my Ender 3.

***See below Re: scale and statues***

Suitable in size (huge) and armament (basically none) to be a Universe-Class Mass Conveyor for the classic tabletop wargame Battlefleet Gothic, and also for games of Rogue Trader. You'll need to dig out your own statues to add, I recommend the following:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2718906

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3413744

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3669457

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:153037

You'll either need to smush them together or tweak them separately and glue them the old-fashioned way. There's two slots either side of the prow, one on the prow upper face behind the large antenna, and one near the stern on the large flat platform. See the render for some examples.

With regards to scale, the BFG scaling is logarithmic so smaller vessels are oversized and larger ones are undersized. This keeps model sizes managable. This model is ~130 mm long, however for a more "correct" size it should be around 200 mm (1.5x).

I am not affiliated with GW in any way! Please don't reupload this on Shapeways and the like for commercial use (though you're welcome to upload them to get them printed that way for yourself).

Some connector bitz to use drinking straws as pipes in your scratchbuild wargaming terrain.

For a long time now I avoided using drinking straws in my wargaming scenery builds because i simply didn't like the bending part. It always squished and looked arkward.
Today i came up with this rather simple but effective solution. 3D printed connectors!

The drinking straws I had had a inner diameter of 6.6mm.

If your drinking straws have a different diameter just calculate the needed scaling using the excel sheet i added or by hand [("your diameter" x 100) / 6,6]

There is a version of each connector with and without the part that goes into the drinking straw to secure it.

A library building designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support a unit placed on top for all 23 hex locations. It is 6 levels tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are two files. One has the building on hexes and the other is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle. Further, there is a second variation of this building, uploaded as â€œLibrary 1Aâ€ here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4598463

The difference between the two buildings is that 1A is the "original" version, and for 1B the faces that extend from the side of the upper part of the building do not extend as far. If you do not print at a high enough resolution then the bottom part of those faces may sag slightly on 1A. This is not an issue if you print at a high resolution, and can clean up well if you do experience sagging, but you may choose to use 1B to speed up the print time by lowering the resolution, or because your printer resolution cannot go high enough to print those extra faces without issue. 1B makes the building design less prominent, but it means that if you print the building at a low resolution then those parts won't sag at the bottom.

Notable features:
-Detailed design including doors, windows, loading docks, steps to an exterior walkway around the building, and a detailed roof area with greebles such as ducting.
-Visually interesting exterior design.
-The second floor has a curved wall supporting the larger floors on the upper part of the building. This means that the building should print without any supports, and conveniently it is also how the real life building is designed.
-This building is closely based on a real life building. It is designed as a library, but you could use it as an office building or something else if you're creative.
-This building is fairly large and would provide a great addition to your urban terrain.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

Here's a fully remixed fleet for the Mechanical Spaceships - full credit to Italianmoose for creating such an amazing set of models.

Why a remix? I've cleaned up the files a fair bit and added some nice extras to make them more practical for the tabletop.

All options are magnetized - 2x1mm holes for Prow and Weapons Battery choices. Each option has been designed to be WYSIWYG - torpedo tubes, matching lance/weapons batteries from the rulebook to make any combination.

All Hulls are magnetized for 4x2mm flight stands which I've also included - this is perfect for keeping them stable without any issues, tried and tested!

Each hull has an "Embossed" set of prows and hulls. This is so you can choose to have logos or not.

"The Nova Cannons are underslung?!" Yes. I struggled to get them to fit correctly in a way I was happy with. Included are Stock prows and separate Nova Cannon files if you want to add them on yourself, and in the future I may add them as additional files.

[UPDATE 12/9/20] Added Armored Prow Pack (LC rules allow an upgraded prow at the cost of mobility, why not roll them out for all options! Once again significantly modified from Italianmoose base files for Imperial Battleships.)

The Scroggan Ambush Truck is a common improvised low-tech design found on many back-water planets that typically lack their own dedicated FightMech force or other standing professional militaries. The Scroggan Ambush Truck typically mounts 2x SRM-6s and is designed for a single-shot surprise attack, initiated at close range.

The improvised nature of this method of attack often means that the SRM fire-system is burned out during the initiation, which makes it uncommon for the Scroggan to be able to sustain multiple attacks from the same platform.

To build a Scroggan, a single-salvo SRM pod is usually grafted to whatever cargo moving truck is available locally and then positioned on likely FightMech approaches.

The Scroggan Ambush Truck ambush method was originally used on Thingerse III (in the Deep Periphery) in Jun 3020. In this minor action, a well-equipped force of invading FightMech Pirates was temporarily halted in their advance through the planet's urban capital by several Scroggans. Antonius Scroggan, an officer cadet wash-out from the nearby Taurian Constellation who had settled on the planet, organized several small ambushes that delayed the pirates by at least several days.

Scroggan subsequently blew himself up while wiring in some SRM pods incorrectly, and the Pirates soon claimed Thingerse III - despite the harassing inconvenience imposed by a few remaining trucks and minor damage sustained to several ankle actuators.

In tongue-in-cheek homage to Scroggan, the Pirates afterward referred to this method of singe-shot, low-blow, but largely ineffective ambush as the 'Scroggan Cheap-Shot.'

These are my versions of the Nova and Gladius Frigates from that no longer available tabletop game of epic space battles in the Gothic Sector. I have patterned these after those found on the electronic game of the same name. I have tried to get the scale correct and I hope they are close. I really enjoyed making them and they look awesome printed!

All of them were test printed on an FDM printer at .08 layer height with a .4 nozzle. Angle them up at 45 degrees and be careful while removing supports.

I have placed a starter 3mm hole in the bottoms. I use a 1/8 drill bit and 1/8 styrene rod.. but use what you would like.

These were made from scratch using base primitives.

Suitable in size and armament for a stand in for any of the cruisers for the classic tabletop wargame Battlefleet Gothic. This is a little chunkier in design to make it easier to print on FFF printers. The segments all fit together, though they may need some filing depending on printer. Other widgets, including a Nova cannon, at: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3489166
(Thanks for the reminder about them, Hanskrampf!) (Also not my designs)

I am not affiliated with GW in any way! Please don't reupload this on Shapeways and the like for commercial use.

2018-10-05 Added a version without the domes to act as a battlecruiser hull, can't believe I forgot!

2019-03-24 Added a new prow, with thicker ribs and a more sleek shape. Added extra bits to the engines to make the transition between the main hull and engines less jarring. There is also now a void for a pin underneath the hull. Check your slicer doesn't fill the hole, and drill through the circle on the lower hull.

2023-05-20 - Added headless and eagle-less prows on request for kitbashing. Enjoy!

Remix of various Knight parts with some custom CAD parts to flesh it out, bare hulls to allow for Armour swaps. Pre-Scaled to print at 1:1.

I added struts to some of the overhangs that were difficult to add supports to so you can string them off those (particularly the on the legs)

Note when adding the rear hip cables glue the middle first then when that is set use a hairdryer to heat up the resin and bend the ends into place (use a toothpick or the tip of your scalpel to add the superglue).

The carapace is fairly tight of a fit around the exhausts. I used a needle file to bevel the lower part of the hole and glued it on before painting.

Also included the following:
- Remix of "Quest bot Magaera upgrade AT" by TrueGrits617 - I split up the files into individual parts plus reversed the layout of the carapace and added some grab handles to make it more accurate to the 40k version
- Included some files with supports already added mine printed fine on the Photon with these where they are.

Added 14/08/19 -
- Hekaton Claw Arm with both the Styrix and Mahaera Claw Tips.


Added 15/08/219 -
Styrix Pattern Head, well a fair approximation, in High Poly model.


Serious Note: This was a personal project, to test to see how far I could push the detail on my Photon. it would have been far easier for me to just buy the plastic kits and remix just the armour and weapons lol

An AT18 Rescale and Remix of Jimbeamz Lucius Wardog. I removed some iconography and modded a couple of bits plus merged some and added pre-done holes in the torso. Its not perfect but it should work and is fairly close in height to one of the official plastic Mars Pattern Kits. Please note I have not done the Plasma or Flamer weapons yet. I will upload them when they are done.

Notes:
- Primarily aimed at being printed on a DLP Printer
- Parts are not merged so if you want to repose the legs feel free.
- If GW release a plastic version of this I will be removing it. At the moment it is an unavailable kit so I'm posting this in good faith for free.
- Do not request re-ups of the original 40k Scale file. I won't be doing that.


Edit 05/02/2020: Added remixed Turbo Plasma and the Plasma Canisters for it.

Edit 06/02/2020: Found Three Rivets I missed removing that floated in space under the Turbo Plasma, added a fixed version of the file. If you downloaded on day one grab the new file.

Edit 08/02/2020: Noticed some weird artifacting in the plasma gun when you slice it. Specifically there appears to be an invisible block extending in the core of the weapon into the socket for the arm mount. I'll have to work out which addition is causing this and clean it up manually. If you print it out before then you will need to dremel or drill out the socket. I'll try and fix this when i get some time off work.

This is a proxy representing a Rogue Trader Brigantine from the out-of-print board game Battlefleet Gothic, from Games Workshop.

It contains some elements from other authors. I've used the imperial cruiser from Italianmoose as an inspiration to get the general look, so it blends with the rest of the imperial fleet (although I've given it a more sports-like look), but I've also taken some parts directly from the original model. The statues of the hull are from Harrowtale, but sadly on a FMD printer you will only get the basic shape. The connections of the Side_A and Side_B parts are at 61mm height which is the same than the height of the Ferratonic Furnace connection. The diameters of these are 26mm and 40mm.
________________________

-Added a second "front" part with minor enhanced details
-Added a grating that goes to the front part to cover the pipe opening
-Added a second ring with a pipe connection at the top. The overall height here is 122mm which is exactly the samt than the Sector Mechanicus parts (Ferratonic Furnace and walkways)
-Added base_V2: allows you to put Side_B parts at both sides
-Added base_V3: which is like base.stl but without the side pipe connections
-Added a second Version of the side parts Side_A_V2.stl and Side_B_V2.stl
-Added a second example assembly HR_V2.stl
<b>Update 2:</b>
-fixed an error with SIde_A and Side_B: the small pipes where floating which caused bad print
-Added a cut(15mm) in Side_A and Side_B in the middle to make space for a magnet on the pice connection

A Thunderhawk Ordinance proxy for Battlefleet Gothic.

A game buddy asked for some prints and I couldn't find a suitable model.

As per 2nd pic...
- The scale is based on the Imperial Attack Craft Models by Mkhand_Industries
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2626812
- The shape is heavily borrowed from a similar model on $h@p#w@y$.

While i very much like Mkhand's models (and have printed a number for my Imperial fleet) i've found that the wings are very delicate on my filament printer... as such the thunderhawk wings are all a little chunkier (minimum 0.5mm).

Has now been netfabb'd.

Have test printed. works but it's like tiny tiny (as per last pic).
Re pic: the small ones are what the file produces. the big one is 250% scale just to test that stuff was there and printing.
Re other pic: (not finished) paint just to add some colour.
The teeny-tiny ones do look ok once they're on stands. And there's a fair amount of tricky support cleanup. enjoy.

Note: For my marine fleet i've printed these at 133%. just to get a bit more 'detail' and less blobbular. these are the yellowish ones. note that for sticking them to the bases i just use some chopped filament, was easier than printing the bases with stands as they were coming out horrible.

These designs utilized Renafoxs' - Ruined Cars (Small Freebie) set as a framework to build upon. His/Her car model works are found on Sketchfab ( https://sketchfab.com/models/632d4eb3ebbd4796b1353e5691c92edd ) and distributed on a non-commercial license. 

A wide collection of choices includes;

- flipped vehicle
- 1 of 3 variations of head-on collisions
- 1 of 2 variations of parking meter collisions.
- 1 of 2 variations of street lamp/electrical pole collisions.
- 1 of 2 variations of fire hydrant / mail box collisions.

You can inverse all designs if you want more variations of collisions.

** Noting these models have gone through meschmixer and netfabb to correct-all non-noticible collision errors, compression-errors and should be slice-safe - they may however needs some minor touch-ups connecting axis-variables for overhanging poles where your slicing software ignores minor joint imparement and supports.


** UPDATE **

Pick-up truck that hit a log included!
